David Sternlight (strnlght@netcom.com) wrote:
: At last, an expert.

: There has been a lot of screaming and shouting about how RSA could not be
: patented in the European Community because it is:

: 1. a patent on an algorithm;
: 2. a patent on a computer program;
: 3. a patent on a mathematical formula.

: all of which are asserted not to be patentable in the EU. (I exclude the
: prior publication issue which was not the subject of that discussion.)

: Associated with that family of discussions has been the assertion by some
: that it "should not" have been patentable in the U.S. for the same reasons.

: Could you please clarify just what kind of U.S. patent RSA represents? Those
: I trust have asserted that it is a "system" or "process" patent rather than
: any of the above, and thus would be patentable in the European Community.

While I _could_ post copies of sample claims here from the RSA patent, it 
would not be considered appropriate for me to comment further on this or 
any other issued patent, sorry.

Basically, the claims start off by reciting:

A communications system, ... 

or

A communications method, ...
